		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Reena]]></dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Tue, 06 Jan 2015 20:04:13 +0000</pubDate>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">https://jamesclear-com.uar9g7bv-liquidwebsites.com/?p=6424#comment-13975</guid>

					<description><![CDATA[I just wanted to say that I started reading your blog last New Year when someone posted your &#039;dont&#039; have goals&#039; article on Facebook. From there, your blog became one of my favorite ways to consistently refocus my energy this year. I really appreciate the bi-weekly reminders to apply these simple, thoughtful concepts to my life and work, and I have also enjoyed sharing your ideas with the people around me. 

More specifically, I took your advice all year, not to have goals but to focus instead on setting up processes and letting them run their course, whatever that may be. It was very scary to do this, because this year was my final semester of doctoral coursework (orals, comps, dissertation), and I was simultaneously working full time and running an organization. I started the year not knowing how I was going to get everything done (focusing on goals would have completely sunk me), but instead, I just got up and worked in a specific way every day, and trusted that it would all work out. I just wanted to tell you: It did work out! While it was intensely difficult, it would have been completely impossible if I hadn&#039;t changed my mindset about how to make progress.

Thanks for this wonderful, positive, authentic blog! As we move into 2015, I&#039;m grateful to be part of this community.]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>I just wanted to say that I started reading your blog last New Year when someone posted your &#8216;dont&#8217; have goals&#8217; article on Facebook. From there, your blog became one of my favorite ways to consistently refocus my energy this year. I really appreciate the bi-weekly reminders to apply these simple, thoughtful concepts to my life and work, and I have also enjoyed sharing your ideas with the people around me. </p>
<p>More specifically, I took your advice all year, not to have goals but to focus instead on setting up processes and letting them run their course, whatever that may be. It was very scary to do this, because this year was my final semester of doctoral coursework (orals, comps, dissertation), and I was simultaneously working full time and running an organization. I started the year not knowing how I was going to get everything done (focusing on goals would have completely sunk me), but instead, I just got up and worked in a specific way every day, and trusted that it would all work out. I just wanted to tell you: It did work out! While it was intensely difficult, it would have been completely impossible if I hadn&#8217;t changed my mindset about how to make progress.</p>
<p>Thanks for this wonderful, positive, authentic blog! As we move into 2015, I&#8217;m grateful to be part of this community.</p>
